Combining the information for vertex skinning
In the standard glTF format, there are two options for including
external binary resources like buffer data and textures: They
may be referenced via URIs, or embedded in the JSON part of
the glTF using data URIs. When they are referenced via URIs,
then each external resource implies a new download request.
When they are embedded as data URIs, the base 64 encoding
of the binary data will increase the file size considerably.
To overcome these drawbacks, there is the option to combine
the glTF JSON and the binary data into a single binary glTF
file. This is a little-endian file, with the extension ".glb", which
contains a header, the scene description (usually UTF-8
encoded JSON), and the body with the binary data.

The skins summarize the information from
which the skinning matrix is computed. The
skinning matrix describes how the vertices
of the mesh are transformed based on the
skeleton pose. It is computed from joint
matrices, which in turn are computed from
the information that is provided by the skin.
Each joint that is referred to via one of the
jointNames in the skin may influence the
vertex positions of the mesh. For each of
these joints, one joint matrix is computed.
The node that contains the skinning
information also refers to meshes to
which the skinning should be applied.
The mesh primitives of a skinned mesh contain the usual
POSITION attribute that refers to the accessor containing the
vertex positions. Additionally, they contain two special attributes
that are required for skinning: A JOINT attribute and a WEIGHT
attribute, each referring to one of the accessors.

The glTF format allows specifying the materials that should
be used for rendering objects. These materials are based on
techniques, which in turn refer to programs consisting of
vertex- and fragment shaders. This brings unlimited flexibility,
but also makes it necessary to specify many details about the
materials and the shader source code even for simple scenes.

The inverseBindMatrices of the skin refer to one of the accessors. The
accessor data consists of one inverse bind matrix for each joint. This
matrix transforms the mesh into the local space of the respective joint.
A glTF may contain the information that is necessary to perform
vertex skinning. A node that refers to meshes may therefore
also refer to a skin, and to "skeletons". Together, these describe
how the vertices of the mesh should be influenced by the bones
of the skeleton, based on its current pose.
